        <!-- INTRODUCTION -->
        <p id="intro" class="paragraph">
            The Philippines is one of the <b>most connected countries in Southeast Asia</b>, with millions of Filipinos spending hours each day on <i>social media, online banking, and digital commerce</i>. This deep digital engagement, while beneficial for communication and economic growth, has also made the country a <b>prime target for cybercriminals</b> who exploit the online presence of everyday users. <b>Cybercrime in the Philippines has grown rapidly over the past decade</b>, affecting individuals, businesses, and government institutions across the nation. As technology becomes more embedded in daily life, understanding these digital threats becomes not just useful but <i>necessary for everyone</i>. This article explores the current state of cybercrime in the Philippines, its most common forms, why Filipinos are frequently targeted, and what is being done to fight back.
        </p>


        <!-- BODY 1 -->
        <h2 id="landscape">The Growing Cybercrime Landscape in the Philippines</h2>
        <p class="paragraph">
            Cybercrime has become one of the <b>most serious digital security concerns in the Philippines</b> in recent years. Reports from the <i>PNP Anti-Cybercrime Group (ACG)</i> show a consistent year-on-year rise in the number of complaints and cases filed. The <b>National Bureau of Investigation (NBI) Cybercrime Division</b> has similarly recorded an increasing caseload, reflecting how widespread these offenses have become. The COVID-19 pandemic played a significant role in accelerating this trend, as more people shifted to online platforms for work, school, and commerce. Cybercriminals quickly took advantage of this shift, launching new schemes targeting remote workers, online shoppers, and digital banking users. Even after the pandemic, the number of Filipinos online has continued to grow, expanding the pool of potential victims. According to the Department of Information and Communications Technology (DICT), the Philippines ranks among the top countries in Asia for social media use. This high level of connectivity, combined with gaps in digital literacy, creates the perfect environment for cybercrime to thrive. Awareness of this growing landscape is the first and most important step in addressing the problem.
        </p>


        <!-- BODY 2 -->
        <h2 id="common-crimes">Most Common Cybercrimes Affecting Filipinos</h2>
        <p class="paragraph">
            Several types of cybercrime are especially prevalent in the Philippines, and understanding them helps individuals recognize and avoid potential threats. <b>Online scams</b> are the most commonly reported, often involving fake sellers on social media marketplaces who collect payment and disappear without delivering goods. <b>Phishing attacks</b> trick users into revealing personal or financial information through fake websites or deceptive messages that appear to come from trusted sources like banks or government agencies. <b>Identity theft</b> occurs when criminals steal personal data to open fraudulent accounts, apply for loans, or impersonate victims. <b>Account hacking</b> on social media platforms is also rampant, with stolen accounts used to scam the victim's friends and family. <b>Online sexual exploitation and trafficking</b>, particularly of minors, is a deeply serious issue that Philippine authorities actively investigate and prosecute. <b>Ransomware attacks</b> have also targeted local businesses and hospitals, encrypting their data and demanding payment for its release. Below is a summary of the most frequently reported cybercrimes in the Philippines:
        </p>

        <table>
            <tr>
                <th>Type of Cybercrime</th>
                <th>Description</th>
                <th>Common Targets</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><b>Online Scams</b></td>
