            </tr>
        </table>


        <!-- BODY 3 -->
        <h2 id="why-targeted">Why Filipinos Are Frequently Targeted</h2>
        <p class="paragraph">
            There are several key reasons why the Philippines is a frequent target of cybercriminals both locally and internationally. First, Filipinos are among the <b>heaviest social media users in the world</b>, spending an average of several hours online each day, which exposes them to a wide range of digital threats. Second, the rapid growth of <b>mobile banking and e-wallet services</b> such as GCash and Maya has created new opportunities for financial fraud, especially among users who are new to digital transactions. Third, many Filipinos, particularly in rural areas and older age groups, have <b>limited cybersecurity awareness</b> and may not recognize the signs of a scam or phishing attempt. Fourth, the widespread use of <i>public Wi-Fi networks</i> in cafes, malls, and schools makes it easier for hackers to intercept data. Fifth, many devices used in the Philippines run <b>outdated or unpatched software</b>, leaving known security vulnerabilities unaddressed. Sixth, the <i>language barrier</i> in understanding cybersecurity advisories written in English can prevent some users from acting on important warnings. Finally, the growing popularity of <b>online freelancing and remote work</b> among Filipinos has expanded their exposure to international scams and digital attacks. Taken together, these factors make Filipinos an attractive and accessible target for cybercriminals.
        </p>

