        <h2 id="impact">Impact of Cybercrime on Victims and Society</h2>
        <p class="paragraph">
            The effects of cybercrime go far beyond financial loss and touch on the emotional, psychological, and social well-being of victims. <b>Financial damage</b> is often the most immediate consequence, with victims losing savings, investments, or earnings to scams and fraud that are difficult or impossible to recover. Beyond money, many victims experience <b>emotional distress</b>, including anxiety, shame, and depression, especially when they feel responsible for falling for a scam. <b>Reputational harm</b> can occur when stolen social media accounts are used to spread misinformation or solicit money from the victim's contacts, damaging personal and professional relationships. Victims of <i>identity theft</i> may face long and complicated legal processes to clear their name and restore their credit standing. In cases of <b>online sexual exploitation</b>, the trauma can be lifelong and deeply scarring, often requiring psychological intervention and legal support. At the societal level, widespread cybercrime erodes <i>public trust in online platforms</i>, digital banking, and e-government services, slowing down the country's transition to a digital economy. Businesses that fall victim to cyberattacks may suffer <b>data breaches, operational disruptions, and loss of customer confidence</b>. Small and medium enterprises (SMEs), which form the backbone of the Philippine economy, are particularly vulnerable as they often lack the resources to invest in robust cybersecurity systems. Addressing these impacts requires both institutional action and individual vigilance.
        </p>


        <!-- BODY 5 -->
        <h2 id="response">Government Response and How to Stay Protected</h2>
        <p class="paragraph">
            The Philippine government has taken concrete steps to combat cybercrime through legislation, law enforcement, and public awareness campaigns. The landmark <b>Republic Act 10175, or the Cybercrime Prevention Act of 2012</b>, criminalizes offenses such as hacking, cybersex, online libel, and identity theft, and provides the legal basis for prosecuting cybercriminals. The <b>SIM Registration Act</b>, which took effect in 2023, requires all mobile phone users to register their SIM cards, making it harder for criminals to use anonymous numbers for scams and fraud. The <i>PNP Anti-Cybercrime Group (ACG)</i> and the <i>NBI Cybercrime Division</i> actively investigate cases, coordinate with international agencies, and run public information campaigns. The <b>Department of Information and Communications Technology (DICT)</b> has also been working to strengthen the country's national cybersecurity framework and develop incident response capabilities. On a personal level, Filipinos can protect themselves by practicing <b>strong password management</b> — using unique and complex passwords for each account. Enabling <b>two-factor authentication (2FA)</b> adds an extra layer of security that makes it significantly harder for hackers to access accounts even if they obtain a password. Being cautious of <i>suspicious links, unsolicited messages, and unknown callers</i> asking for personal information is equally important. Regularly updating apps and operating systems ensures known vulnerabilities are patched. Most importantly, <b>reporting suspicious activity</b> to the PNP ACG or NBI helps authorities track and respond to threats more effectively.
        </p>


        <!-- CONCLUSION -->
        <h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>
        <p class="paragraph">
            Cybercrime in the Philippines is a serious and growing threat that affects people of all ages, backgrounds, and income levels. The country's high internet usage, rapid adoption of digital financial services, and gaps in cybersecurity awareness have made it a frequent target for both local and international cybercriminals. Common crimes such as online scams, phishing, identity theft, and ransomware cause not only financial harm but also lasting emotional and social damage to victims. Fortunately, the government has put in place meaningful legal frameworks and enforcement mechanisms to address these threats, and public awareness is slowly improving. However, legislation alone cannot solve the problem — every Filipino internet user has a personal responsibility to stay informed, practice safe online habits, and report suspicious activity. <i>Education and awareness remain the most powerful tools</i> in the fight against cybercrime. By working together — citizens, businesses, and government — the Philippines can build a <b>safer and more secure digital future</b> for everyone.
        </p>

